	<div class="posts">
	<a name="108506809901305685">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h3>Why Indeed, Awkward Software</h3><a href="http://www.rattlesnake.com/notions/why-awkward-software.html">Why Awkward Software?</a>.&nbsp; Robert Chassell asks why usability and the human factors around use of, say GNU/Linux, aren't being addressed by the big-company supporters like IBM.&nbsp; I don't know either, although I can tell you that it will take a while.<br /><br />I lived with the DB2 personal edition for about 8 weeks and discovered that attention to installation lifecycle and learning curve of the user is not addressed very well, and this is presumably a mature product.&nbsp; The only worse recent experience was applying SQL Server security patches to the copy of MSDE that is installed with Microsoft Office Extensions.  <br /><br />I'm not sure how one can drown out the geek echo long enough to figure out what works for the rest of the people.&nbsp; Most geekware is not anything I want to put in the spotlight either.&nbsp; We should stop assuming software is designed any better for geeks than for anyone else.&nbsp; Maybe producing graceful software simply requires a higher level of skill and attention and, most of all, a commitment to genuine, measurable usability by the intended community of users.&nbsp; That probably requires more practice at simply looking, listening, and asking.&nbsp; Refusing to make it up would be particularly nice.<br>
